{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_oliver_ver01/data/sn83045462/00280600556/1930111601/0099.xml":{"full_text":"A-2\nSHIPSTEAD CHIDES\nPOLITICAL LEADERS\nt\" i 1\nKith Parties Missed Chance\n|to End Depression, He\nSays, Urging Action.\n\n5 (Continued From First I\nB might u constituting, In my\nt, under correction, a program\na conducive to increased pros\nall times and calculated, there\nto to impede but to promote\nty now. I believe included in\nigory are\nThe Wagner btlle for the re-\nUif of unemployment.\nPublic work, including in\nland waterways and a public building\nConservation and control of\ntlpn of courts or equity in certain cbsee.\nPrevention of the inflation\nMid deflation of credit.\nIf Sixth. A better balanced distribu\ntion *f national Income,\nifgeventh.- The tariff.\"\nChides Party LeMers.\nJThe statement of the seven Demo\ncratic leaders promising co-operation\nwith the administration in the new\nCongress, and acceptance of the offer\nby. Republican leaders, suggests to Ben\nasPr Shipstead that the leaders of both\nparties are at.last tempted to embrace\nOBorge Washington\u2019s opinion that \"the\nspirit, of party serves always to dis\ntrict the public councils and enfeeble\ntire public administration.\u201d\nSVith sarcasm suggesting amusement,\nBJflpstead welcomed \"their conversion.\u201d\n\u2022\u2018lnstead of following Washington we\ntoday have seemingly to a large extent\nsubmerged our loyalty to State and\ncountry In favor of loyalty to this or\nthat political party,\u201d he said.\ntTYet, now when the country most\nparticularly needs salvation, the lead\nen of both major parties unite in pro\nposing and accepting an abandonment\nof-* party and a recurrence to the prin\nciple of George Washington, the prin\nciple of non-partisanship toward the\nsolutions of the difficulties of the Re\nwelcome their conversion. I hope\nt|py will persist In it. I hope they will\ncontinue to put country above party\nnot only In an emergency, but normally\nmd uninterruptedly.\u201d He added that\nho took both parties at the \"literal\nWWrth\u201d of their progressions. \"It is\nWild, in the first place,\u201d ho Said, \"that\ntgward the problems which this crisis\npresents we should be entirely political\nly non-partisan. In this view f heartily\nconcur. I concur in it not only at this\ntfcpe, but at all times.\u201d\nText of Addres.\niisenator Shipstead's address follows,\nfUe full:\n:2 am grateful for the honor of speak\nfold; to you this evening through the\ntesy of (me of our greatest national\nr newspapers, The Washington Star\nWashington, D. C.\nshall speak to you with\u2014l hope\ns' .full sense of what is due to this mo\nment of special economic crisis. Two\ndental attitudes toward It an being\nwidely stressed.\n\u20223t is said, in the first place, that\ntoward the problems which this crisis\npresents we should be entirely politically\ndan-partisan. In that view I heartily\nqincur. I concur in it not only at this\nfine but at all times. X apeak neither\ndr the Republicans nor for the Demo\ndots, neither for the administration\ngbr tor the opposition. Nor do I aeeums\nU speak for any one else,\nj? You an frequently told that we must\ngovernment by partied.- You arc\nfpld^lmi^^rty\u00dfoyalty, party discipline.\nMid execution of party policy, axe \u2018Ole\nplvstion of the country. I nave kept\n(I mind a warning ot Washington, whW\ntt his farewell address to his country,\ndarned them to beware of \u201cbaneful\nH political parties In the\nWashington who in that\ndeclared that \"the spirit\na always to distract the\ni and enfeeble the public\nIt la. the spirit, said\nthat agitates communities\nLed jealousies and false\ni animosities, a spirit not\ned in purely elective gov\nttnments,\u201d and that la the kind of a\nGovernment ours is supposed to be.\nThis was the fear of political parties\ngby George Washington and\nils sentiments, for what he\nit as true today as when he\ne words more than a century\ntad of following Washington\ntmve seemingly to a large ex\nerted our loyalty to state and\ni favor of loyalty to this or\nsal party. Yet, now when the\ntost particularly needs selva\nleaders of both major parties\nproposing and accepting an\nent of party and a recurrence\nnciple of George Washington,\n>le of non-partisanship toward\nms of the difficulties of the\nRepublic.\nI welcome their conversion. I hope\ntttey will persist In It. I hope they will\nContinue to put country above party\npot only in an emergency but normally\nfind uninterruptedly.\nDesirable to Be \u201cConstruetire.\u201d\nL We then come to the second attitude\nwhich at this moment Is recommended\nJb us. We are told that we must now\nB\u00bb not only non-partisan but \u201ccan-\nItructlve.\u201d Again I heartily concur. X\npad supposed, indeed, that It was de\n\u25a0rable at all times to be \"constructive.\u201d\nft had not supposed that either party\nspy time would bring forward\nmeasures intended to be \u201cdestructive.\"\nP\u00bb any case, however, I join earnestly\nIp the suggestion that we should today\nM-aad-then perhaps even tomorrow\u2014\nBase entirely from being \u201cdestructive\u201d\nBid negative and become wholly \u201ccon\n\u25a0nictlve\u201d and positive.\ngWe must, therefore, look about for\nideas for positive ideas,\nhe ideas lately dominant in the man\nlament of the country were very eon\nderably repudiated by the people at\nto polls last week. The party which\ni the Senate and in the House of\nepreeentatives was the beneficiary of\nvat repudiation now says that its main\nlea will be to \u201cco-operate\" with the\nuty which was the victim of that\nspoliation. Surely there must be\nunewhere some Idea more \u201cconstruc\nve,\u201d more positive, than the Idea of\nso-operation\u201d with ideas which the\nxwtry has found unsatisfying.\nDoubtless in time each party will\nmflde to you its new ideas for curing\njr newly emphasized distresses. They\neve not yet, as parties, done so. There\ni talk of the danger of what is called\npocking the boat/\u2019 That la a phrase\nhlch M too much employed to excuse\nring nothing whatsoever to improve\nlewagz We are led toward thinking\nvat the proper remedy In a storm Is\nglslaUve Inaction. I take It, on the\nantripjp, that If It is \"constructive\" and\nositlve to equip a boat with a good\nngtne and e good rudder and a good\nompase in fair weather. It is still more\nconstructive\u201d and positive to give It\nvat helpful equipment when, in Its\n(Tort to survive the storm. It most\needs it.\nX accordingly take both parties at the\nteralmnth of their professions. We\ncould now be non-pertleanly open to\nteas and we should be \u201cconstructively\"\nnd positively, if we can be, creative of\nleas. \u201cConstruction\u201d Is doing aome\ni\u00dfg. There are many things which,\nt my judgment, we might properly\nmg ago have done to strengthen the\noat In which we are sailing our na\nlonal bourse. I advocate them to\nigfai as constituting, In my judgment,\nnder correction, a program of action\nondudve to increased prosperity at ail\nfoW and calculated, therefore, not to\nmpodebttt to promote prosperity how.\nIn Mild el \u25a0ealjastmewt.\nWe are ft the midst of a moat mo\n~\u00abK\u00dftous itStfjusUnent of trade end to\ndustry. Individual initiative la at a\ngverrthina tends Jr-\nI SPEAKS 'IN NATIONAL RADIO FORUM\nSENATOR HENRIK 6HIFSTEAP.\nreststibly toward concentration. The\nOlder competitive methods are now re-\nSirded as wrong totally archaic.\nusiness is done in conventions, groups,\ninstitutes. Even the Government now\nsubmerges the individual and enforces\nco-eperation. Chain retail stores force\nthe older distributors to undertake co\noperative buying and we face the pos\nsibility of Nation-wide concentration of\nthe money power through holdtng com\npanies, bank stock corporations and the\nlike. The dislocation, unemployment\nand turmoil of this great overturn ac\ncounts, in my Judgment, for as much of\nour present confusion as the stock mar\nket losses of a year ago.\nMany causes have contributed to this\nfeverish era of change\u2014overproduc\ntion, destruction of buying power\nthrough an unfair distribution of in\ncome, the exportation of capital to build\nindustry in foreign countries, satura\ntion of world madwts and the urge to\nstimulate business in order to carry\ngreat structures of loan and bond issues\nthrough inflation of capital and credit\nitructurN*\nThese conditions are recognised every\nwhere. The remedy cannot be left to\ntime alone. The question is what can\nwe do now to relieve the hasard and\nsuffering of the emergency and to re\nlieve anxiety and uncertainty for the\nfuture.\nI believe included In this category are:\nFirst The Wagner bills for the re\nlief of unemployment.\nSecond. Public works, including In\nland waterways and a public building\nConservation and control of\nnatural resources.\nFcurth Restriction of the jurisdic\ntion of courts of equity to certain cases.\nFifth. Prevention of the inflation\nand deflation of credit.\nSixth. A better balanced distribution\nof national Income.\nSeventh. The tariff.\nControl of National Reeonrees.\nIt Is generally conceded that a con\nstructive program of legislation for the\nconservation and better control of our\nnational resources of water power, oil,\n1 timber and public lands must be en\nacted to the near future. A legislative\nremedy must also be found to pratort\n1 the constitutional rights of citizens\nfrom abrogation through the misuse\nof the injunction power by courts of\nequity. But. this evening I will discuss\nto detail only a few measures intended\nto relieve us to the present emergency.\nA Federal building program has\ntkwdr been inaugurated with a gen\nmomi authorisation of $520,000,000, and\naoDrooriations will undoubtedly be en\n-1 larged to complete the program and\n1 aid in the relief of unemployment.\n1 However, a primary problem to which\na targf conittueUve contribution can\nbe iwm* by Federal legislative enact\n-1 menu is the problem of Involuntary\nunemployment. The routes toward\nthat contribution are three in number.\nI They haver all been diligently explored\nand expressed in proposed enactments\nby Senator Wagner of New York.\nfirst is that there should be\nthroughout the country a genuinely\nInterconnected system of permanent\nl employment-finding public agencies,\nmunicipal and State and Federal held\n1 together for comprehensive effort by\nFederal leadership and by \u00bbme con\n-1 slderable appropriations of Federal\ni money.\ni The second Is that the Federal Oov\neminent should furnish to State gov-\nI ernments and to local governments a\ncompelling example In the accumula\ntion of a reservoir of plans and of\nfunds for the execution on a large\ntesto of public works, such as build\nings and waterways and roads and\nharbor Improvements and the like, In\nftnms of unemployment emergency.\nThe third Is that the Federal Gov\nernment should blase the way toward\na survey of all the existing and\nprospective possibilities in the direc\ntion of the establishment, whether by\nKvate effort or by public effort or by\nh of a system of scientifically cal\nculated insurance against the miseries\ncaused to our working population and\nthe losses caused to our business com\nmunity by unemployment crises.\nTill these three objectives have been\nreached the Federal Government can\nnot be regarded as havtfcg fulfilled Its\nlegislative duty In the emergency now\nCredit Legislation Needed.\nX believe that legislation can and\nshould be enacted to prevent as far as\npossible the wrongful use of credit. The\nnew theory of economics that has been\nespounded In recent years based on the\ntheory that the way to become prosper\nous is to \"buy what you do not need and\nmay not be able to pay for Is a bad\ntheory and destructive In practice. Xt\npromotes extravagance and waste end\nundermines character. Buying what we\nneed and can pay for is good economics\nend good morals for the Nation as well\nas for the Individuals. Careful thinkers\nhave long felt that a more careful hus\nbanding of credit Is a paramount need.\nLuxuries should be bought out of capi\ntal account and not with borrowed capi\ntal The extension of credit for specu\nlation when speculation assumes the\nproportions of pure gambling is wrong\nful use of credit and a legislative remedy\nmust be found to curb this practice.\nMuch a remedy should aid In preventing\nperiodical cycles of inflation and defla\ntion of the credit structures with result\nmg disastrous fluctuations of prices.\nI believe that legislation now In force\nla In past responsible for the malad\njustment of the distribution of the na\ntional Income. Readjustment Is im\nperatively necessary.\nThe theory has been advanced that\nbusiness and agriculture are suffering\nfrom overproduction. This In my opin\nion la only true In a limited degree.\nInflation of credit always stimulates\nproduction. The Invention and use of\nnew machinery has also stimulated pro\nduction. but on the other hand, X be\nhave we are suffering from under\nconsumption or a lack of ability to\nbuy the poods produced because of the\nunequal distribution of Income. Gov\nernment statistics reveal that from lilt\nto ltM the total value of farm crops\ndropped over 43 per cent. X venture\nto Mg that there has been no substan\ntial improvement In the economic situa\ntion of our farmer! since these reports\nwere published.\nLabor ft An Shew Drop.\nAccording to, ft* statiaUcal table of\ntheDwrtmen\nTHE SUNDAY STAB, WASHINGTON, D. C., NOVEMBEB 16, 1930\u2014 PART ONE.\nIS per cent from ID2O to 1026. The\nsame report sheftrs that the monthly\ntotal average pay roll of wages declined\n30.1 per oent during the same six years\nThe Bureau of Labor Statistics in Its\nmonthly report for May, 1927, reported\nthat the quantity for manufactured\ngoods per wage earner employed has\nincreased 24 per cent in the preceding\nseven years. The average workman in\nthe mill* and factories was in 1927\ngiving his employer a yearly product 34\nper cent greater than he was seven\nyears before. The drop of 30 per cent\nin labor\u2019s share of the national lnoome\nwas due to the drop of 18 per cent In\nemployment because during the same\ntime the average working employe had\nan increase in wages of 9 per cent. On\nthe other hand the President\u2019s Confer\nence on Unemployment in its report,\n\u201cRecent Economic Changes,\u201d shows that\nafter paying dividends of preferred\nstock, interest on bonded Indebtedness\nand other expenses, corporations en\njoyed an increase in dividends on com\nmon stock from 164 In 1923, with 1913\nas a basis of 100, to 230 In 1926, an\nIncrease of 66 points, or 40 per cent.\nThis disparity of income could, in the\nend, bring only disaster to Industry be\ncause Industry cannot buy Its own prod\nucts. Industry must look for a mar\nket for its products to the 70 millions\nof people working on the farms and to\nIndustry, but with their Income declin\ning 42 per oent and 30 per cent re\nspectively they cannot buy and Indus\ntry is now suffering from the back\nwash of the resulting economic up\nheaval\nIf industry is to have a market for\nits products to its natural field, which\nla the American producers, wise indus\ntrial leaders will see that they must co\noperate to enacting legislation to place\nagriculture on a par with industry now\nin order that agriculture and labor may\nshare to the national Income with in\ndustry in proportion to the value of the\nservices rendered. This is necessary If\nwe are to have a balanced economic na\ntional life. Industry can also help to\nabolish, to pari, this disparity of income\nby one of two ways or both. Either by\nIncreasing the aggregate income to labor\nthrough wages, a shorter labor week or\nby reduced prices for manufootored\ngoods to the consumers. The inequal\nities of the tariff law should be illumin\nated and the tariffs on Agricultural\nproducts not now effective should be\nmade effective by enacting legislation to\nput into operation the debenture plan df\nfarm relief, or some other method by\nwhich tariffs on agricultural products,\nof which we now export a surplus, can\nbe made effective.\nSeeks Transportation Relief.\nI believe relief from high transporta\ntion charges to and from the sea ie an\nimperative need for the land-locked\nterritory of the Mississippi Valley. De\nvelopment of the inland waterways will\ngive this relief.\nThe railroad rate-making formulas of\nthe Interstate Commerce Commission\nunder the Esch-Cummins acr and the\ndevastating effect on the landlocked\nMidwest of the construction and opera\ntion of the Panama Canal are In large\npart responsible for the dislocation of\nindustry and the prostration of agricul\nture to this great Inland region. The\nconsequent decrease to invested capital\nand in men employed has resulted In a\ncorresponding loss In home markets to\nMidwest agriculture. Theee are not\nconditions to bs remedied by the slow\nworking of time. Their correction rests\nin so far as that is possible with the\nGovernment that helped to create them.\nThey represent issues which face those\nof us now active in commercial and\npublic affairs.\nCongress has to aid of trade, industry\nand agriculture authorised the develop\nment of a system of inland waterways\nfor the Mississippi Valley, the cost of\nwhich will approximate 6265,000,000.\nThe amount, however, required to be\nappropriated for the completion of all\nriver and harbor projects now author\nised to about $500,000,000. It to of the\nutmost national Importance that all\nthese projects be completed to the\nshortest time possible, not in excess of\nfive years. This opinion to based upon\nthe following considerations:\nFirst, the depressed condition of\ntrade, industry and agriculture calls for\nrelief now through the savings which\nwill be available from transportation on\nimproved waterways.\nSeoond. Economy In Government\nfinancing. The present piecemeal\nmethod of proeecutlng the work on\nthese projects under thehandteap of\nuncertain annual appropriations will\nrequire 20 yean for thrir completion.\nConservative calculations disclose that\npiecemeal methods of the past Increases\nthe cost at least 40 per cent over\noriginal estimates and authorisations\u2014\nwitness the Ohio River, which was esti\nmated to cost $83,600,000 and actually\ncost after 20 years of piecemeal work\nin excess of $100,000,000. A five-year\nprogram on already authorised river and\nharbor projects would, therefore, save\nto first cost approximately $330,000,000.\nThird. Savings in interest on capital\ninvested and unproductive during the\naverage period ox construction of some\n20 years under present piecemeal meth\nods will amount to $162,500,000.\nFourth. We are facing a serious un\nemployment problem. Private capital\ncan help but cannot remedy th; present\nsituation. Industry is already over\nexpanded. The present state of business\nand securities calls for retrenchment.\nThe whole river and harbor program\nwhich to a reproductive public work,\nshould m pressed to completion. Directly\nor indirectly 500,000 men would thereby\nbe given employment during the next\nfive yean.\nFinancial Program Null!\nFifth. Industry would, if a definite\nshort term of years was officially estab\nlished for the completion of our inland\nwaterways, anticipate their completion\nas It did on the Ohio, and construct\nplants and facilities now, thus employ\ning added labor and capital.\nThere remains for consideration a\ni financial program. Two methods sug\ngest themselves to me. We are retiring\nr our war debts at the rate ot $1,000.-\ni 000,000 per year. We can postpone this\nretirement program for one year and\napply a sufficient amount thereof to\ncomplete our entire river and harbor\nprogram, or Congress can authorise a\nbond issue, as was done to build the\nPanama Canal, for the immediate\nprosecution of an approved rlvsk and\nt harbor projects to bs completed*!* five\nyears. Great liquidations of our war\nl debts axe throwing back upon the hands\nSHOW SPONSORED\nTO AID MEMORIAL\nMachinists Arrange Benefit\nMidnight Performance\nto Raise Funds.\nThe premier showing of \u201cSee America\nThirst, a comedy, is to be offered on\nThanksgiving eve, Wednesday. Novem\nber 26, at the Rialto Theater at a mid\nnight show for the benefit of the Dis\ntrict of Columbia World War Memorial.\nColumbia Lodge. 174, International\nAssociation of Machinate, known as the\nNavy Yard local, is sponsoring the\nshow as their contribution to the big\ncampaign now on to complete financ\ning of the War Memorial here.\nFTank w. Lee, chairman of the Spe\ncial Committee in charge, who to vice\npresident of the Mount Vernon Sav\nings Bank, and chairman of the Wash\nington Central Labor Union Executive\nCommittee to charge of raising $20,000\nfor the War Memorial announced last\nnight that plans were also being msde\nfor some surprtonig features of a popu\nlar nature in addition to the big fea\nture picture of the midnight show.\nThe Rialto Theater management to\nco-operating with Columbia Lodge,\n174, in a campaign to make the occa\nsion a success, contributing substan\ntially to the campaign to erect the\nDistrict World War Memorial.\nCHARGE OF THREAT\nMADE BY JURORS\nIN VETERANS\u2019 CASE\n(Continued From First Page.)\nagreement before his return later in\nthe evening. The jurors asked for\nfurther Instructions about 8 p.m., and\nJustice Siddons returned to the court\nhouse for the purpose and then sent\nthem back to confer further. No in\nformation was given the justice that\nthe jurors had not been fed, and his\nattention was not called to the fact\nthat there to no longer dormitory space\nto the court house tor the accommo\ndation ot civil Jurors detained over\nnight. So he knew nothing of their\nplight.\nCompelled to Go Hungry.\nDeputy Marshals McCarthy and Den\nham, in charge of the Jury, sought\nvainly to get the jurors to agree to go\nto dinner, but were met with state\nment* that an agreement was immi\nnent, and at least one Juror refused to\nKwhen told that the jurors would\nv# to pay their own way. The\nothers were compelled to go without\nfood, as the marshal could not separate\nthem. Objection was also made by\nsome of the panel when advised that\nthey would be expected to pay for hotel\naccommodations, since the marshal\u2019s\noffice hss no longer space to house\nthem and his appropriation for main\ntenance of Juries applied only to crim\ninal cases.\nForeman Wilkins, when the hour was\napproaching midnight, took money from\nhis pocket and gave it to Deputy Mc-\nCarthy to obtain a quantity of sand\nwiches from a nearby lunch room, the\nproprietor of which added a quantity\nof coffee when the situation was ex\nplained to him.\nText ot Affidavit.\nThe affidavit signed by Wilkins reads:\n\u201cThat I was foreman of the jury in\nthe case of Paul Beale vs. United\nStates Veterans\u2019 Bureau; that after\nseveral ballots tt was evident the Jury\ncould not agree; that the members of\ntte jury had no supper for the reason\nthat one juror favorable to the plain\ntiff refused to go to supper until a ver\ndict was reached; that the time between\nballots was quite disorderly, some of\nthe jurymen indulging to vile and\nabusive language toward those holding\nout for the defendant; that Jurors\ncursed and swore at jurymen favorable\nto the defendant because they would\nnot agree with them upon a verdict;\nthat such expressions as \u2018Yes, you\nsnip, just because you are a college\nman you think you know more than\n10 men\u2019 and \u2019because you are a busi\n-1 nets man you think your judgment\ncan be right and 10 wrong\u2019 were\ndirected against jurors favorable to the\ndefendant; that such actions at times\nalmost precipitated a fight; that one\ntime a juror favorable to the defendant\nwas called a liar by a juryman favorable\nto the plaintiff and the latter assumed\na belligerent attitude toward the jurors\nfavorable to the defendant; that about\n11 o'clock the affiant requested the\ndeputy to have sent to some coffee and\nsandwiches, for which the affiant paid\nwith his personal funds; that the jury\nhad no place to sleep; that finally about\n0 am. o\u2019clock the jurors favorable to\nthe defendant weakened by lack of\nfood and loss of sleep, rather than re\nmain until 10 o\u2019clock, when the court\nwould convene, decided to give in, which\nthey did, and that the verdict was\nbased purely on sentiment snd not in\naccordance with the law and the facts\nIn the case, and he further states that\nthe foregoing occurences detailed by\nhim Influenced him to the extent of\nagreeing to the verdict, and that the\nverdict was not based wholly upon\nthe law and the evidence to the case.\u201d\nSimilar statements are contained In\nthe affidavit of the other juror.\nIn asking for a new trial and the\nsetting aside of the verdict against It\nthe United States Veterans\u2019 Bureau,\nthrough United States Attorney Leo A.\nRover, Assistant United States Attorney\nJohn W. Flhelly and Attorney Annabel\nHinder liter claim that the verdict Is\ncontrary to the evidence and was ob\ntained through misconduct of the jurors\nor some of them.\nWheat Pool Pressing Denied.\nWINNIPEG, Manitoba, November 16\nOP). \u2014Rumors that lending banks were\npressing the wheat pool to liquidate its\nholdings were strongly denied today by\nofficers of the banks. The rumors cir\nculated the floor of the grain exchange\ntoday and were believed to have had\nconsiderable Influence on the sharp de\ncline to values.\n\nof our citizens large sums of Idle money.\nCapital requirements for the develop\nment of trade and industry are at a\nminimum. Idle capital pays no Income\ntax. Under present conditions this\ncapital can be secured through an In\nternal loan at rates lower than avail\nable in recent times. I believe this a\nsound use of Government credit. Not\nonly capital, but materials are at the\ni lowest scale of recent years. This Is\nthe time for a forthright, a definite and\ncourageous financial program to com\nplete our inland waterways, not only to\nrestore In so far is possible trade rela\ntions in the Midwest destroyed in large\npart by governmental action, to the\nconstruction of the Panama Canal and\nthe operation of the Esch-Cummins act,\nbut to employ idle capital, to stimulate\nbusiness, to relieve unemployment and\nto aid agriculture. The develojunent of\ntheee inland waterways was advocated\nby the President to on address at Louis\nville a year ago and I believe the Nation\nat large will welcotne such a program.\nWhen these maladjustments have\nbeen corrected by constructive legisla\ntion and if we continue to keep free\nfrom political entanglements with for\neign countries aa was Indicated by Pres\nident Hoover to his Armistice day ad\ndress when he said, \"The security of\nour geographic situation, our traditional\nfreedom from entanglements to the in\nvolved diplomacy of Europe and our\ndisinterestedness enabled us to give a\ndifferent and to many ways a more\neffective service to peace,\u201d we shall have\na return of prosperity, continued peace\nand a healthy growth of our national\nm.\nPOUND TO ELECT\nSEJM TOMORROW\nMarshal Pilsudski Hopes for\nSupport\u2014City Aflame With\nExcitement.\nBx the Associated Press.\nWARSAW, Poland, November 15.\nPoland's 15,006,000 voters tomorrow will\nchoose 444 members for the Sejm, or\nParliament.\nA largely increased government ma\njority was generally expected over that\nof the last Parliament, which consisted\nof 118 pro-government, 216 Polish op\npositional and 83 national minlorlty\noppositional deputies.\nPilsudski Seeks Support.\nThe only question that remains Is\nhow many opposition deputies will be\nelected, despite the fact that 81 opposi\ntion members of Parliament are in Jail,\nseveral party candidate lists ruled out,\nvarious organs of the national minior\nlties, such as German and Ukrainian,\nsuppressed, and. according to opposi\ntion estimates, some 5,000 citizens ar\nrested in the course of the campaign.\nMarshal Pilsudski, after trying In\nvain since the 1926 coup d\u2019etat to se\ncure a government majority in the\nSejm, abruptly dissolved that body last\nAugust. The marshal\u2019s plea to the\nelectorate has been that Parliament as\nheretofore constituted, has hamstrung\nthe government and made constructive\nwork impossible. He hss insisted that\nmore power be given the President, at\nleast to enable him to veto decisions of\nParliament.\nSince only a three-fifth majority can\nchange the constitution, Pilsudski de\nsires at least 300 pro-government depu\nties elected.\nElection Excitement High.\nThe city was aflame with pre-election\nexcitement tonight, and so much cam\npaign literature was distributed the\nstreets appeared at times to be covered\nwith snow.\nSome disorder occurred in the Jowisch\nquarter, inhabited by Jews, whers cer\ntain groups said to be Zionists battled\nOrthodox Jews in a political dispute.\nThe alleged Zionists pulled the long\nbeards of their Orthodox brethren and\nwere themselves belabored with sticks.\nPREMIERHAMAGUCHI\nSHOWS IMPROVEMENT\nPhysicians Report Temperature of\n99.5 Degrees After Batiefac\ntory Night.\nBy the Associated Press.\nTOKIO, November 16. Premier\nHamaguchl, shot and wounded severely\nFriday by an assassin, supposed patri\notic fanatic, had a satisfactory night\nand at 6:30 a.m. today was sleeping\npeacefully. His temperature was lower,\n99 5 degrees.\nPrayers were offered today in Budd\nhist Temples for the recovery of Pre\nmier Hamaguchl.\nHamaguchl was said by physicians\nstill to be to death\u2019s shadow.\nWith Intestines pierced by a bullet\nfired while he was at the central rail\nroad station, the premier was given\nthree or more blood transfusions. It\nwas felt unsafe to attempt removal of\nthe bullet from his left thigh.\nPhysicians, however, said Hamaguchl\npassed the sero hour of peritonitis men\nace at noon and \"thus far was prog\nressing satisfactorily.\u201d\nAlthough the political situation re\nmained undisturbed. Foreign Minister\nShidehara became acting premier dur\ning incapacity of his chief.\nPolice holding Sagoya in close con\nfinement refused to make public what\ncaused him to attempt the death of\nthe government\u2019s head. Members of\nthe Love of Country Association, the\n23-year-old assassin was thought men\ntally deranged by prolonged opposition\nto the Hamaguchl government which ac\ncepted the London Naval Treaty.\nIn procuring treaty ratification by\nEmperor Hirohlto, Hamaguchl said\nJapan, in attempting lees warship ton\nnage allocation than Japanese naval\nand other critics demanded, would gain\ninternational good will.\nI\nI I FORMER SECRETARY SUES\nCLARA BOW FOR JEWELS\n$5,000 Damages Also Asked in\nAction Naming Actress and\nDistrict Attorney.\nBy the Associated Press.\nLOS ANGELEB, November 15.\u2014Daisy\n1 Devoe, discharged former secretary to\nClara Bow, red-headed film actress,\nfiled suit in Superior Court today\nagainst Miss Bow, her cowboy actor\nfriend, Rex Bell, District Attorney\nBuron Fitts and three of his investi\ngators for recovery of Jewelry and other\narticles valued at $2,200.\nMiss Devoe charged the district at\ntorney with wrongfully holdtng her\nproperty at the request of Miss Bow,\nand with seising it without proper\nprocess of law.\nShe demanded also $5,000 exemplary\ndamages, charging she had been the\nvictim of \"malice, fraud and oppres-\nslon.\u201d\nDOUBLE BLOWS CUT\nNEW YORK\u2019S LIQUOR;\nTWO BOATS SEIZED\n(Continued From First\ntraffic is the result of secret \"John\nDoe\u201d indictments returned by a Fed\neral grand Jury. The exact nature of\nthe charges will not be revealed until\nthe Indictments are opened Monday.\nAmong syndicate members still at\nlarge are several radio operators, offi\ncers said. They were employed in\nsyndicate-owned shore stations for the\ntransmission of instructions to syndi\ncate boats. Under radioed directions\nthe smaller boats would take aboard\nliquor from ocean-going steamers and\nwould then be guided by radio to shore\nstations, where vans and trucks await\ned to transport the liquor to ware\nhouses. It was two such warehouses\nthat yielded the liquor seized by the\nprohibition agents last night and today.\nCmh Killa Pilot.\nKING WOOD, W. Va., November 15\n(A*).\u2014Reginald Shaw. 22, of Klngwood.\nwas killed today when his airplane fell\nand burned near the Klngwood Air\nport.\nLee Highway Link\nTo New Market Is\nOpened to Traffic\nBy the Aseocieted Press.\nRICHMOND, Va.. November 15.\n\u2014The final length of construction\non the Lee Highway, United States\nRoute 211, between Washington,\nD. C., and New Market is now\nopened >to traffic, the weekly report\nor highway conditions issued today\nby the State Department of High\nways said.\nWith the sec tt on completed there\nla now a paved rogW from Washing- 1\nton to tiie Shenandoah Valley by\nWarrenton and Sperryvllle.\nCuba and Revolution\nGuggenheim*s Support Is All That Holds Mechedo\nin Power \u2014Mendieta Seen as Next President\nShould Present Administration Fell\nBY WILLIAM HABD.\nHerewith follow some verbal por\ntraits of some of the chief uprlaera\nagainst President Machado in Cuba.\nEvery realist here\nFresMaat MsahsSe.\nIn Was hi n gton\nknows that Just\none slender thread\nnow holds Presi\ndent Machado In\npower. That Is\nthe support given\nhim by the United\nBtales Ambassador\nat Havana, Harry\nF. Ou( g e nhelm.\nAdvised by Mr.\nGuggenheim, the\nState Department\nhas bettered Cuba\nto be pacified and\nhas so told the\nnewspaper corns- j\nspondents. Today\nCuba is again in\neruption and Mr. Guggenheim as an ad\nviser and pacifier of Cuba Is himself\nhanging by a slender thread. A change\nof administration In Cuba, with or with\nout physical armed Intervention by the\nUnited States, seems potentially Immi\nnent. If It happens, the following Cu\nban celebrities will be prominent in the\nnew Cuban era and will be seen in news\nreels and heard In movie-tones through\nout this country.\nVarona la Philosopher.\nKnrique Jos Varona\u2014One of the two\nliving former Vice Presidents of Cuba.\nCuba\u2019s acknowledged highest philoso\npher. He has written great book* so\nhigh that many even of his closest\nrelatives will not climb up to pull them\ndown from the shelves. He is cne of\nthose men with an immense In ter no\ntional reputation for writings which\nmost people will not read, preferring to\ncontent themselves with reading about\nthe reputation. He is very old, perhaps\nalmost 90, and any word that he lets\ndrop from his altitude of fame and of\nage are carefully picked up to put into\nany newspaper that President Machado\nallows to be published. The words that\nVarona has recently dropped have been\nIntended to make dents In the Machado\nadministration.\nEx-Presidents in Limelight.\nMario G. Menocal\u2014He was Presi\ndent of Cuba for eight years, ending In\n1925. There la only one other living\nCuban former\nPresident. Meno\ncal turned against\nMachado only a\nshort time ego. He\nis solid and cau\ntious in tempera\nment. He is slen\nder in physique.\nHe is quiet In\nmanner. He speaks\nEnglish. He is a\ngraduate of Cor\nnell University at\nIthaca. N. Y. He\nis a civil engineer\nand was general\nl manager for many\n1 years of the Ou\nban-Amer lean\nSugar Co., an ex\nMarie G. MenocaL\ntremely extensive enterprise. He is of\ngood family. His appearance is one\nof great unadventurousness. He Is pre\ncisely what most people in this country\ndo not think of when they think of a\n\"Latin American revolutionist.\u201d\nDomingo Mendes Capote.\u2014The other\nliving Cuban ex-vice president. One\ndeep trouble of Machado\u2019s is that both\nCuban ex-presidents and both Cuban\nex-vloe presidents now living are de\ntermined to make him also an \u201cex-.\"\n\u201cEx-\" marks the spot of the resigna\ntion. Mendes Capote Is short, stout,\nsteady, self-controlled. He is a lawyer.\nHe has been a representative In Cuba of\nlarge United States financial interests.\nHe is conspicuous socially. He and\nhis wife are among the very \"best\ncircle\u201d people. Senora Mendez Ca\npote. however, though circulating in\nsuch circles, seems also to be capable\nof tangents. She went off the other\nday at the head of a column of social\nregister ladles in Havana to inarch\nupon the local barracks, there to urge\nthe officers not to fire upon uprisers\nagainst Machado. She is reputed to\nhave expressed the opinion that things\nANTMIEPEAL STAND\nBY CRIME BODY DUE\nNational Prohibition Refer\nendum Not to Be Approved\nin Report to Hoover.\nBy the Asaoelatstf Frew.\nA decision against repeal of the\neighteenth amendement had been\nreached yesterday by President Hoover\u2019s\nLaw Enforcement Commission and the\nactual writing of its prohibition report\nwas nearer than at any time during\nthe past 17 months.\nAlthough a final decision on the\nrecommendations to be included was\ndescribed as still in the offing, some\ngeneral agreement has been reached,\nand not only repeal but 4 per cent beer\nor any request for a national prohi\nbition referendum were authoritatively\nreported out of the picture.\nMay Aid 5M Men.\nMeanwhile, those charged with the\nenforcement of prohibition as it now\nstands were busy on figures to be pre\nsented to the House Appropriations\nCommittee, Including among other\nthings the cost of adding 800 additional\nmen to the enforcement personnel.\nAt the same time, however, Repre\nsentative Byros, Democrat, Tennessee,\nranking minority member of the House,\nwho has supported every prohibition en\nforcement measure voted by Congress\nIn the past decade, made a statement\nthat he would reserve a decision on the\npresent addition of 500 dry workers. He\nasserted he did not feel there had been\n\u201ca deep yearning to enforce prohibi\ntion.\"\nOnly a few of the 11 members of the\nHoover Law Enforcement Commission\nwere here yesterday. Technically freed\nof their task by a-10-day recess, they\nnevertheless worked on statements that\nwill be laid before the whole commis\nsion when It reconvenes November 24.\nUnder present plans five or six state\nments will be ready by that date, and\nwith these before them the members will\ndiscuss the tentative conclusions, pos-\nslbly change some of them, and weld\nthe whole Into a final report.\nMembers to Write Opinions.\nIt has also been planned to have\neach member, after the task is done,\nwrite an opinion telling how his own\ndecision was reached, and his feeling\ntoward the reoommendatlons to be in\ncluded In the report itself. These will\nbe laid before President Hoover probably\nbefore the end of December.\nJewish Daily Suppressed.\nJERUSALEM, November IS (JF). \u2014The\nRevisionist Hebrew Daily Doarhayom\nwes closed by order of the high com\nmissioner tonight for publishing arti\ncles regarding Jewish self-defense and\nImmigration certificates suggesting the\ngovernment mad* miser concessions to\nthe Jews In ordev to excite the Arabs.\nin Cuba would move faster 11 the wom\nen wore the trousers.\nAlfredo Zayaa\u2014He is the other living\nex-Presldent of Cube. He also la openly\nout for President Machado's overthrow.\nHe had no specially great start In\n1 fl\nAlfred* X.TM.\nyouth. He is\nlargely what is call-1\ned \"self-educated.\u201d\nHe thereupon flu\nently speaks five\nlanguages\u2014S pan\nto, English French.\nGerman, Italian.\nHis outstanding\nreputation is for\nadroitness, astute\nness, political\nfence building,\nSlitlcal wire-puU-\nI. He is sup\nposed to be able to\ndo more without\nmoving from a\ngiven spot or cross\ning his eyes than\nanybody else in\nHavana. In fact, as a political manip\nulator he la supposed to be just about\nthe prise product of all Latin Amer\nica As some degraded wise-cracker\nhM Mid, \"He knows his Spanish\nonions*\" Whatever may happen to any\nbody 4lae, Zayaa is very unlikely to be\nfound assassinated.\nMendteto Has Character.\nCarlos Mendieta\u2014The head of the\nwhole anti-Machado affair. Some 85\nyears old. A physician. He does not,\nhowever, practice. He grows sugar.\nHe does not speak English. He springs,\nas the saying goes, from \u201cthe people.\"\nHe was not born to the purple. He re\nceives no plaudits lor scintillating\ncleverness. There are no anecdotes of\nhim In commemoration of smart sayings\nor of sharp corner maneuvers. He pro\nduces. In hie way, a sort of George Wash\nington effect. Nobody calls him brilliant\nand everybody about him follows his\nJudgment. If Machado falls, Mendieta\nwill almost Inevitably become the next\nCuban President There seems to be no\nbody who would even try to rival him.\nHe has been straight along the leader of\nthe so-called \"Naclonallstas.\u201d who have\noriginated and accumulated the effec\ntive opposition to the Machado regime.\nHe is the connective tissue which keeps\nthe opposition together. The thing\nhe has that does It, so far as any ex\nternal observer can make out Is Just\ncharacter.\nCosme de la Torrlente\u2014He provides\nbrilliance enough. He used to be Cuban\nAmbassador here In Washington. He\nis learned, and loves it. He is fluent,\nand loves it. He is famous\nI H I\nCm\u00ab Tgrritait.\nand loves It. He\nhas been president\nof the Assembly of\nthe League of\nNations. He is an\nintellectualist. He\nloves to spread his\nwings in a maga\nzine article and fly\nto a time when\nCuba shall have\nbeen freed from!\nthe Platt amend\nment, which con\ntinuously carries\nthe United States\nInto Cuba\u2019s Inter\nnal affairs. He is]\nas flashing as\nMendieta is sober-\ncolored. He brings\nto the Cuban \u201cNaclonailstas\" an ink\nwell and a pen that can and do get\nattention for their cause on the other\nside of the Atlantic as well as on this.\nHe has been Mendleta\u2019s publiclst-ln\nchief. He is intimately known either\nfor reputation or in person to all the\nprincipal International publicists of this\ncountry. He is a central reason why\namong such people in the United States\nthe NacionaUsta arguments have had a\nready hearing.\nSuch are a few of the more prominent\nand influential Cuban anti-Machadlstas.\nNumerous American statesmen speak of\n\u201cLatin American revolutionists\" as they\nwould speak of \"Pirates of the Spanish\nMain.\u201d That is too romantic. In Latin\nAmerican countries \"the established\ngovernment\" is some agreeable people.\nThe \"revolution\" is the other agreeable\npeople. i\n(Copyright, mo.)\nPre-Prohibition Beer\nAt Bottom of Well\nFound in Drought\nBr the Associated Press.\nUPTON. Mass., November IS.\n\u2014The well was not as dry as\nDavid Shuber thought it was.\nThe drought has dried up many\nwells in Upton and West Upton.\nWhen the Shuber well ceased to\nfunction. Shuber went down to\nsee what was wrong. He found\nthere was no water, but there\nwere a doaen bottles of pre\nprohibition beer.\nThe beer, buried in mud at the\nbottom of the well, apparently\nhad been there for 11 or 12 years.\nPAINTER AND WIFE HELD\nON CHARGES OF ARSON\nNew York Fire Marshal Says Pair\n\u25b2re Perpetrators of Plot to De\nfraud Insurance Companies.\nBr the Associated Frees.\nNEW YORK, November 15.\u2014Victor\nRosso. 22, Argentine portrait painter,\nand his 28-year-old wife, Amy Laura\nHome Rosso, were arrested tonight on\ncharges of arson as the alleged perpe\ntrators of what Chief Ptre Marshal\nThomas P. Brophy called \"one of the\nmost brazen international plots to de\nfraud insurance companies that has\ncome to my attention.\"\nRosso and his wife conducted an art\ngallery on West Fifty-sixth street, which,\nwas swept by fire of suspicious origin on\nOctober 26. The painter said the fire\ndestroyed 160 paintings and many art\nobjects, which had been imured in Mrs.\nRosso\u2019s name for $266,130.\nThe chief fire marshal said an investi\ngation revealed that quantities of excel\nsior lying about the gallery had been\nsoaked In a liquid that smelled like gas\noline.\nRosso told the fire marshal\u2019s investi\ngators the paintings and his house fur\nnishings had been brought to this coun\ntry from Cordoba, Argentina, on May 8,\n1929, and that the entire shipment\nhad been admitted duty free as house\nfurnishings. He said the paintings and\nart objects destroyed in the Are were\nworth $200,000.\nMarshal Brophy said cables from of\nficials of the Argentine Republic advised\nthat Rosso was listed as the occupant of\na studio In Buenos Aires which was\ndestroyed by fire on January 14, 1927.\nThe contents of the studio had been in\nsured for 100,000 pesos, the cables said,\nand Rosso claimed a loss of 228,000\npesos.\nCOFFEE ROASTERS ELECT\nNSW YORK. November U UP). \u2014The\nfirst official statement of uH Board\nman of Caxsden, N. J., today aSapewly\nelected preside it of the American Cof\nfee Roasters Association assured con\ntinued support and co-operation to tin\ncoffee-growing countries of LaK\nAmerica. A\u2019 T\nB. M. Cofer,T Ban Francisco, vA\nsleeted vice president of the\ntiwfi at its session.\nMADRID DARKENED\nIN 2-DAY RIOTING\nFood and Water Menaoed\nand Martial. Law Threatens,\nWith 100 Wounded.\n\u00bbr the AhwliM Pnu.\nMADRID. No\u00bbwb\u00abr ll.\u2014PiMrt* DM\nSol, tha Timet Square of Madrid, was\ndark and deserted tonight except for\nheavily armed ppUee petrol*; tran\u00bb-\nportation serviees were at a stand\nstill. the city food and water euppUee\nwere menaced and martial law ap\npeared an imminent possibility at the\nend of two days of labor riot*.\nThis day saw brutal fighting in the\n\u2022treats among police and rioters and\nby noon a general strike had called\nout street ear and subway crews,\nworkers at the power houses and\nwater works, pressmen In the news-\nshopa, factory workers and\nFrateetien far UUHtlee.\nAn emergency cabinet meeting or\ndered military protection for the light,\nwater, gas and food supplies: placed\nmilitary trucks at ths disposal of the\npolice for transportation of breed,\nposted a soldier guard in the streets,\nand was believed ready to proclaim\nmartial law the moment it should stem\nnecessary.\nAt least two men have been kilted la\nthe two days, and possibly four. At\nleast a doaen are seriously wounded, a\nhundred others less seriously injured,\nand a hundred or more men have been'\narrested.\nAmusement Places Closed.\nThe general strike is due to end on\nMonday, but meantime, strike head\nquarters have ordered cases, ban,\ntheaters end all amusement resort#\nclosed all dsy tomorrow.\nAll this trouble began Wednesday at\nthe funeral of four building construc\ntion workers who wers killed in a build,\ntag collapse. The funeral services be\nrto w th \u25a0MUog suddenness,\nand not until two men had bean kilted\nwe rioters dispersed. The disorders\ntarok* out answ today with a atriks of\n40.000 construction workers, which wag\nby demonstrations in\n\u2022MM* *,OOO university students par\nticipated.\nDispatches from Malaga said a gen\neral strike of serious proportions was in\nprogress there, and that soldiers had\nordeqid to operate the bakeries.\nwas believed the government was\nstep h*ra\nMORE THANS.OOO\nJOBLESS REGISTER\nWITH LOCAL GROUPS\n(Continued Prom First Pms.)\nand woman. It was stated at schocda\nthroughout the city that tbs registrants\nIC S.L- m *ih-, o l3r Ebou 10 per\ncent of thoee registering being women.\npl4I JD ed to close ths\n\u25a0Chool registration offices at noon yw*\nt\u00abday, but many of the registration\nckrkf. school teachers who volunteered\nfor the work, found themselves swamped\nhy the unexpected number of reads*\nand stayed hours after the clos\ning hour getting all their cards filled\nout and waiting until the last jobless\nm\u00abn or woman had bean served.\nregistration\u2014s census, in fact\u2014\nforts to remedy the situation will be\nAmount cf information about each reg\nistrant, showing particularly what work\n5* te experienced in. will be\ndovetailed, where possible, with the ap\nplications of employers for help, and\nare expected to simplify the job of\nbringing employer and unemployed in\ncontact\nJOBS INCREASE Iff GROUTS.\nBut Average In IS Industries Drape\nFrom September Figure*.\nThe Labor Department\u2019s Bureau of\nStatistics reported yesterday that em\nployment in anthracite mining, bi\ntuminous coal mining, retail trade and\nproduction Increased\nThe average In IS leading industrial\ngroups, however, the bureau announced,\nwas a decrease of 1.4 per. cent over\nSeptember and a pay roll decline of\nO.S per cent\nThe Increases la anthracite mining\nwere B.S per cent; retail trade was 3J\npar pent; bituminous cdal mining, 1.4\nper oent, and crude petroleum produc\ning. 0.3 per cent\nExcluding manufacturing, the IS se\nlected industries showed a decrease of\n2.2 per oent in the number of em\nployes. but a gain .of 0.4 par oent In\npay roll totals. Manufacturing indus\ntries reported a decrease of 1.4 per oent\nin workers and S per cent in pay roll\ntotals.\nOn November 13 the Industrial em\nployment information bulletin of the\nLabor Department said there had been\n\u201cpractically no increase in the volume\nof unemployment as compared with\nprevious months.\u201d\n\"This in itself is a good stem,\u201d ths\nbulletin said, \u201cas October is often\nmarked by increased idleness due to\nseasonal influences. With all Govern\nment agencies, States and municipali\nties co-operating to stimulate employ\nment, we are hopefully looking forward\nto an improved situation.\u201d\nWHEAT HELD AT LOW\nFIGURE IN TRADING\nFluctuation Held to Quarter Cent,\nWith Price at 73 Cents.\nFigure at Winnipeg 58.\na\nBy the Associated Press.\nCHICAGO, November IS.\u2014A day of\ntrading, described by veteran observers\nas without precedent in their mem\nories, kept the Chicago wheat pit in a\nstate of excitement today.\nAlthough buying and wiling oroers\namounting to millions of dollars had\nbeen executed during the session, the\nfluctuation of December wheat was held\nto one-quarter cent, moet-of it going at\n73 cents even.\nDecember wheat, at Winnipeg, mean\nwhile was wiling at as low as 6S cents,\none of the lowest levels ever reached\naccording to traders here. Although\nconfirmation was lacking from official\nsources, local newspapers said the ru\nmor persisted that the Grain Stabilisa\ntion Corporation had contracted for\nsale of 50,000,000 bushels of wheat on\nlong-term credit to Italian buyers.\nIf this were true, the Tribune said\ntonight, it would be the second largest\nsale in American grata annals, ranking\nonly below the 100,000,000 bushfls scdd\nby Julius Barnes after the war to Eu\nropean buyers at mors than $3 a bushel.\nBIBLE TALK SCHEDULED\nRev. R. Dunwoody Walker to Ad\ndress Training flehool.\n\u201cConvincing Testimony\u201d will be ths\nsubject of an address by Rev. R. Dun\nwoody Walker at a meeting of the con\ngregation of the Columbia Bible Train\ning School at the Washington School\nof La*. 3000 O street, this afternoon\nat S o\u2019clock. Rev. Mr. Walker will\nspeak every evening of next week at\nat tha Law school on topics","height":"25257","width":"19659"}}
